\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following the college entrance examination, we have experienced a significant
 transformation in the way we acquire information.
 Instead of passively receiving information from teachers and parents, we
 have taken the initiative to actively comprehend various pieces of information.
 Now, let's explore some intriguing methods that enhance the efficiency
 and simplicity of our information retrieval process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Situation when the Internet was first invented
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After people gained access to the Internet, it became necessary to input
 specific web addresses in order to visit the websites they were familiar
 with.
 In their quest for a better browsing experience, people devised the following
 tricks:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Certain valuable websites will be placed into bookmark bars, facilitating
 convenient access for users.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There are online communities that enable us to share intriguing links with
 one another.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Numerous websites have incorporated their own integrated search tools, allowing
 users to easily search for specific content within their platform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Users leverage their own proactiveness, personal networks, and meticulously
 curated resource collections to make the process of information retrieval
 even more seamless and efficient.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One suggestion is that: Is it feasible to devise a method for aggregating
 all this content into a single platform?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Question
If you were someone aiming to integrate all the available information at
 that time, how would you go about designing it?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aspiration at that time was to have a single keyword that could connect
 all the knowledge together.
 Therefore, they needed a text-matching method to locate the relevant content
 from the existing resources.
 For example, let's assume the document library contains the following text:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Boxed
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
